717065f.title: Manhattan: Broadway - Liberty Street
717065f.text:
Broadway, at, ad;oining and north of the N. W. corner of
Liberty Street (left, not shownl, showing the site of the
Later date Singer Building.
No. 161 Broadway, the five story building contains, the
Knickerbocker Life Insurance Co., the Columbia Fire Insur-
ance Co., and the Yonkers-New York Fire Insurance Co. The
1atter might be the re-organized firm consisting of the sep-
arate companies that failed in the Boston fire of 1871. This
structure was the home of the Greenwich Insurance Co. in the
1890's. An illustration showing this occupancy appears on
page 643 of Moses Kings Handbook of New York, 1893.
The Ailliamsburg City Fire Insurance Co. occupies the store
of No. 165. This firm was organized in 1853. They later moved
to their newly completed (about 1885) home across the street
(N. E. corner of Liberty St.)
For purposes of information, the various remaining insurance
companies after the fire of 1835 were required to orranige in-
dividually and were prohibited from accumulating functions.
They were required to be chartered for specific purposes, such
as fire, life, fidelity, casualtv, etc. On the repeal of the
Act of 1829, many foreign firms (aainly English) entered this
field. After the second conflagration in the business center
of New York (1845), an association of city underwriters was
formed that developed into the National Board in 1866.
